{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RTJur3CEPVVJeUknKcDZaA","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Phase 12-D Review — codex gpt-5.4 verdict\n2\t\n3\tReviewer: `codex --model gpt-5.4 --sandbox read-only`.\n4\tTarget: branch `phase-12-D-durability-harnesses-20260517T185755Z` HEAD\n5\t`df7456b`.\n6\tBaseline: `23292b1` (close of Phase 11 + context-mgmt infra on\n7\t`0.6.0-rewrite`).\n8\tCherry-pick: `b70fbca` / `2a1c203` / `89c7300` on `0.6.0-rewrite`.\n9\tReview log: `dev/plans/runs/12-D-review-20260517T191833Z.log`.\n10\t\n11\tSandbox note: reviewer could not write this file directly (read-only\n12\tsandbox). Main thread promoted the verbatim verdict from log line\n13\t~4750+.\n14\t\n15\t## Verdict: CONCERN\n16\t\n17\t### 1. [high] `probe_wal_sidecar` reads the entire WAL file on every open\n18\t\n19\tRefs:\n20\t\n21\t- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3024`\n22\t- `dev/acceptance.md:580`\n23\t\n24\t`probe_wal_sidecar()` uses `std::fs::read(&wal_path)` just to inspect\n25\tthe header. That makes `Engine.open` pull the full `-wal` sidecar\n26\tinto memory before SQLite does its own recovery work. On large\n27\tunclean-shutdown WALs, this is a real open-path latency and RSS\n28\tregression, and it directly risks the later AC-035 recovery-time\n29\tbudget. The schema-probe change is not the main latency concern\n30\there; the full-file WAL read is.\n31\t\n32\t### 2. [medium] AC-034b drops some trials from the p99 instead of measuring across all P-PWR-TRIALS\n33\t\n34\tRefs:\n35\t\n36\t- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:95`\n37\t- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:128`\n38\t- `dev/acceptance.md:568`\n39\t\n40\tThe harness records `lost_commit_ms: Option<u128>`, filters out\n41\t`None`, then computes p99 on the surviving subset. It only requires\n42\tthat 90% of trials have at least one surviving commit. That is\n43\tweaker than AC-034b's stated measurement \"report p99 across\n44\tP-PWR-TRIALS trials,\" and it means the parent never actually\n45\tguarantees that each victim committed at least one row before\n46\t`SIGKILL`.\n47\t\n48\t### 3. [medium] AC-035c's lock-release check is same-process, not sibling-process\n49\t\n50\tRefs:\n51\t\n52\t- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_open_path.rs:286`\n53\t- `dev/acceptance.md:608`\n54\t\n55\tThe test reacquires `.lock` with a second fd in the same process\n56\tand calls `flock` there. That is useful signal, but it is not the\n57\tdocumented measurement, which requires process A to fail open and\n58\tsibling process B to observe the lock as acquirable. Given the\n59\texplicit AC text, this is a partial proof, not the full contract.\n60\t\n61\t### 4. [low] The AC-034c ignored test is informative, but its body is a stub\n62\t\n63\tRefs:\n64\t\n65\t- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:238`\n66\t\n67\tThe `#[ignore]` reason is good and points at the missing VM/sysrq\n68\tsubstrate, but the body is intentionally empty. If someone clears\n69\t`#[ignore]` without implementing the harness, the test would pass\n70\tvacuously. This is not a current false green because it is ignored,\n71\tbut it is not a runnable placeholder.\n72\t\n73\t## What passed on inspection\n74\t\n75\t- The `open_locked` reorder is directionally correct: header and\n76\t  schema probing now happen before `journal_mode=WAL`, which\n77\t  prevents header/page-1 and schema-btree corruption from being\n78\t  misclassified as WAL replay.\n79\t- AC-035b is asserted per fixture for all four documented rows.\n80\t  Tests check exact `kind`, `stage`, `recovery_hint.code`, and\n81\t  `doc_anchor`. Code-stability test checks both string equality\n82\t  and pointer equality for the `&'static str`.\n83\t- `serial_guard()` is taken by every test in\n84\t  `durability_open_path.rs`, not just the AC-035c tests, so\n85\t  same-binary thread/fd contamination is actually serialized\n86\t  away.\n87\t- The thread/fd residue assertions are consistent with the engine\n88\t  lifecycle: reader threads and the projection runtime are only\n89\t  created after `open_locked` succeeds, so a corruption return\n90\t  from `open_locked` should not leave engine-started threads\n91\t  behind.\n92\t- No meaningful large-schema regression from `SELECT COUNT(*) FROM\n93\t  sqlite_schema` itself; schema surface is small and mostly fixed.\n94\t\n95\t## Reviewer process notes\n96\t\n97\t- Read `dev/acceptance.md`, `dev/design/recovery.md`,\n98\t  `dev/design/errors.md`, output JSON, all three commits, and the\n99\t  full `durability_open_path.rs`, `durability_soak.rs`,\n100\t  `tests/support/corruption.rs`, and `src/lib.rs` deltas.\n101\t- `dev/plans/prompts/12-D-durability-harnesses.md` not present in\n102\t  sparse worktree (out-of-tree by design); could not compare\n103\t  against prompt directly.\n104\t- `MEMORY.md` and `feedback_*.md` not present in worktree; TDD\n105\t  claim not independently verifiable from repo files. Git history\n106\t  bundles tests + engine changes together; red-before-green\n107\t  evidence not recoverable from commits alone.\n108\t- Review was static only; harnesses not executed in read-only\n109\t  sandbox.\n110\t\n111\t## Orchestrator triage\n112\t\n113\tAll four findings substantive and actionable. None\n114\tstructural/prompt-induced — orchestrator override not appropriate.\n115\t**Fix-1 remediation required.**\n116\t\n117\t- **Finding 1 (high)**: `probe_wal_sidecar` must only read the\n118\t  WAL header (first ~32 bytes — magic, page-size, salts), not the\n119\t  full file. SQLite's WAL header is fixed-layout; we don't need\n120\t  the frame data. Fix: replace `std::fs::read` with a bounded\n121\t  `File::open` + `read_exact(&mut [u8; HEADER_LEN])`. Add a test\n122\t  that opens a large fixture WAL (e.g. 10 MB) and asserts RSS\n123\t  delta is bounded.\n124\t- **Finding 2 (medium)**: ensure every victim commits at least\n125\t  one row before SIGKILL. Parent should signal \"ready\" via a\n126\t  per-trial sentinel file the child writes after its first commit\n127\t  lands; parent waits for sentinel before scheduling the kill.\n128\t  Then `lost_commit_ms` is `Some(_)` for every trial and p99 is\n129\t  computed across the full P-PWR-TRIALS=100 set.\n130\t- **Finding 3 (medium)**: replace in-process flock reacquire with\n131\t  true sibling-process check. Reuse Sub-2's test-binary-as-victim\n132\t  trick: spawn a child via `Command::new(current_exe())` with an\n133\t  env-var-gated entry point that attempts `flock` on `<db>.lock`\n134\t  and exits 0 if acquired / 1 if blocked. Parent invokes the\n135\t  AC-035c fixture, then asserts the child exits 0.\n136\t- **Finding 4 (low)**: AC-034c body must `panic!()` with the\n137\t  blocker text + a pointer to the missing substrate. Cleared\n138\t  `#[ignore]` without doing the work = test fails loudly instead\n139\t  of passing vacuously.\n140\t\n141\tSpawn 12-D-fix-1 (Opus 4.7 medium).\n142\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3dcf3508-c16d-46fb-9860-076600a60569","uuid":"8a514b4a-6977-4b51-b1bc-d23fd608c133","timestamp":"2026-05-17T19:25:05.498Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/dev/plans/runs/12-D-review-20260517T191833Z.md","content":"# Phase 12-D Review — codex gpt-5.4 verdict\n\nReviewer: `codex --model gpt-5.4 --sandbox read-only`.\nTarget: branch `phase-12-D-durability-harnesses-20260517T185755Z` HEAD\n`df7456b`.\nBaseline: `23292b1` (close of Phase 11 + context-mgmt infra on\n`0.6.0-rewrite`).\nCherry-pick: `b70fbca` / `2a1c203` / `89c7300` on `0.6.0-rewrite`.\nReview log: `dev/plans/runs/12-D-review-20260517T191833Z.log`.\n\nSandbox note: reviewer could not write this file directly (read-only\nsandbox). Main thread promoted the verbatim verdict from log line\n~4750+.\n\n## Verdict: CONCERN\n\n### 1. [high] `probe_wal_sidecar` reads the entire WAL file on every open\n\nRefs:\n\n- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:3024`\n- `dev/acceptance.md:580`\n\n`probe_wal_sidecar()` uses `std::fs::read(&wal_path)` just to inspect\nthe header. That makes `Engine.open` pull the full `-wal` sidecar\ninto memory before SQLite does its own recovery work. On large\nunclean-shutdown WALs, this is a real open-path latency and RSS\nregression, and it directly risks the later AC-035 recovery-time\nbudget. The schema-probe change is not the main latency concern\nhere; the full-file WAL read is.\n\n### 2. [medium] AC-034b drops some trials from the p99 instead of measuring across all P-PWR-TRIALS\n\nRefs:\n\n- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:95`\n- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:128`\n- `dev/acceptance.md:568`\n\nThe harness records `lost_commit_ms: Option<u128>`, filters out\n`None`, then computes p99 on the surviving subset. It only requires\nthat 90% of trials have at least one surviving commit. That is\nweaker than AC-034b's stated measurement \"report p99 across\nP-PWR-TRIALS trials,\" and it means the parent never actually\nguarantees that each victim committed at least one row before\n`SIGKILL`.\n\n### 3. [medium] AC-035c's lock-release check is same-process, not sibling-process\n\nRefs:\n\n- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_open_path.rs:286`\n- `dev/acceptance.md:608`\n\nThe test reacquires `.lock` with a second fd in the same process\nand calls `flock` there. That is useful signal, but it is not the\ndocumented measurement, which requires process A to fail open and\nsibling process B to observe the lock as acquirable. Given the\nexplicit AC text, this is a partial proof, not the full contract.\n\n### 4. [low] The AC-034c ignored test is informative, but its body is a stub\n\nRefs:\n\n- `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:238`\n\nThe `#[ignore]` reason is good and points at the missing VM/sysrq\nsubstrate, but the body is intentionally empty. If someone clears\n`#[ignore]` without implementing the harness, the test would pass\nvacuously. This is not a current false green because it is ignored,\nbut it is not a runnable placeholder.\n\n## What passed on inspection\n\n- The `open_locked` reorder is directionally correct: header and\n  schema probing now happen before `journal_mode=WAL`, which\n  prevents header/page-1 and schema-btree corruption from being\n  misclassified as WAL replay.\n- AC-035b is asserted per fixture for all four documented rows.\n  Tests check exact `kind`, `stage`, `recovery_hint.code`, and\n  `doc_anchor`. Code-stability test checks both string equality\n  and pointer equality for the `&'static str`.\n- `serial_guard()` is taken by every test in\n  `durability_open_path.rs`, not just the AC-035c tests, so\n  same-binary thread/fd contamination is actually serialized\n  away.\n- The thread/fd residue assertions are consistent with the engine\n  lifecycle: reader threads and the projection runtime are only\n  created after `open_locked` succeeds, so a corruption return\n  from `open_locked` should not leave engine-started threads\n  behind.\n- No meaningful large-schema regression from `SELECT COUNT(*) FROM\n  sqlite_schema` itself; schema surface is small and mostly fixed.\n\n## Reviewer process notes\n\n- Read `dev/acceptance.md`, `dev/design/recovery.md`,\n  `dev/design/errors.md`, output JSON, all three commits, and the\n  full `durability_open_path.rs`, `durability_soak.rs`,\n  `tests/support/corruption.rs`, and `src/lib.rs` deltas.\n- `dev/plans/prompts/12-D-durability-harnesses.md` not present in\n  sparse worktree (out-of-tree by design); could not compare\n  against prompt directly.\n- `MEMORY.md` and `feedback_*.md` not present in worktree; TDD\n  claim not independently verifiable from repo files. Git history\n  bundles tests + engine changes together; red-before-green\n  evidence not recoverable from commits alone.\n- Review was static only; harnesses not executed in read-only\n  sandbox.\n\n## Orchestrator triage\n\nAll four findings substantive and actionable. None\nstructural/prompt-induced — orchestrator override not appropriate.\n**Fix-1 remediation required.**\n\n- **Finding 1 (high)**: `probe_wal_sidecar` must only read the\n  WAL header (first ~32 bytes — magic, page-size, salts), not the\n  full file. SQLite's WAL header is fixed-layout; we don't need\n  the frame data. Fix: replace `std::fs::read` with a bounded\n  `File::open` + `read_exact(&mut [u8; HEADER_LEN])`. Add a test\n  that opens a large fixture WAL (e.g. 10 MB) and asserts RSS\n  delta is bounded.\n- **Finding 2 (medium)**: ensure every victim commits at least\n  one row before SIGKILL. Parent should signal \"ready\" via a\n  per-trial sentinel file the child writes after its first commit\n  lands; parent waits for sentinel before scheduling the kill.\n  Then `lost_commit_ms` is `Some(_)` for every trial and p99 is\n  computed across the full P-PWR-TRIALS=100 set.\n- **Finding 3 (medium)**: replace in-process flock reacquire with\n  true sibling-process check. Reuse Sub-2's test-binary-as-victim\n  trick: spawn a child via `Command::new(current_exe())` with an\n  env-var-gated entry point that attempts `flock` on `<db>.lock`\n  and exits 0 if acquired / 1 if blocked. Parent invokes the\n  AC-035c fixture, then asserts the child exits 0.\n- **Finding 4 (low)**: AC-034c body must `panic!()` with the\n  blocker text + a pointer to the missing substrate. Cleared\n  `#[ignore]` without doing the work = test fails loudly instead\n  of passing vacuously.\n\nSpawn 12-D-fix-1 (Opus 4.7 medium).\n","numLines":142,"startLine":1,"totalLines":142}}}
